        "text": "The tetrarch",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "See on Matthew 14:1.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "See on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 14:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That was done (τὰ γινόμενα)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The present participle. Lit., all that is being done.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Was perplexed (διηπόρει)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Used by Luke only. From διά, through, and ὰπορέω, to be without a way out. The radical idea of the compound verb seems to be of one who goes through the whole list of possible ways, and finds no way out. Hence, to be in perplexity. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
